## Platform

{{Declare the project's platform so universal skills (especially
`/release`) can find the right platform-specific extensions.}}

**Platform:** {{ios | web | python | android | backend | universal}}

When this is set, agents read the matching `.claude/<platform>-*.md`
files (e.g. `.claude/ios-task-rules.md`,
`.claude/ios-conventions.md`) alongside the universal
`.claude/task-rules.md`. Multi-platform projects can list more than
one — e.g. `ios + python` for an iOS app talking to a Python API,
or `web + python` for a web frontend with a Python backend.
Agents will read all relevant prefix files for cross-boundary work.

If `universal`, only the unprefixed kit files apply — useful for
docs sites, libraries, or projects whose platform isn't yet
represented in the kit.

The `/release` skill detects this declaration first, then falls
back to inferring from manifest files (`*.xcodeproj` → ios,
`pyproject.toml` → python, `package.json` → web, etc.).

## Macro architecture (orchestrator)

If this project is a sub-repo of a multi-stack company, the
cross-repo architectural truth — stack inventory, contracts,
conventions, ADRs, migrations — lives in the company's
**orchestrator** repo (built from
[claude-orchestrator](https://github.com/ChazzCoin/claude-orchestrator)).
Set the path:

**Orchestrator path:** `{{ABSOLUTE_PATH_TO_COMPANY_ORCHESTRATOR or "n/a — solo project"}}`

When set, agents read these orchestrator files alongside this
project's own context:

- `<orchestrator>/stack/inventory.md` — what every sub-repo is and
  how they relate
- `<orchestrator>/contracts/` — data models, endpoints, events
- `<orchestrator>/conventions/` — naming, error handling, auth
- `<orchestrator>/features/<x>.md` — any active feature plan
  matching current work

Also check `.claude/active-migrations.md` (and any other
`.claude/active-*.md` files) on session start, per `task-rules.md`
"Active orchestrator notices" — those are written by the
orchestrator's `/migration` and similar skills, and list cross-repo
coordination signals affecting this codebase. Do not edit them by
hand.

If the orchestrator path is `n/a — solo project`, the
"Active orchestrator notices" rule in `task-rules.md` doesn't apply
to this repo.

